@node IML-162 " MSG-162  Subject: Re: Altitude mapping and RAM requirements"

Subject: Re: Altitude mapping and RAM requirements
Date: Wed, 20 Jul 1994 00:04:25 -0400
From: blaq@io.org@planet8.sp.paramax.com

I just did a quick test, and we're both right. Yes, Imagine will use less
memory
if a brush has a smaller palette -- but the difference is minimal. I created a
test 2-color brush, and saved is as a 2-color image, and an identical 64-color
image. Doing a quickrender of a mapped torus, I checked my always-updating
DiskMaster memory display. In both cases, I jotted down free RAM when Imagine
stopped allocating memory and the %complete display started moving. The
difference in free RAM between a 320 x 200, 2-color picture and an identical
64-
color picture was... 148 bytes. So for all intents and purposes, what I said
stands: Imagine converts everything to 24-bit,so you might as well use it. And
a
smart way to use it is to rescale down brushes that consume too much memory.


                         @{"  -=> RETURN TO CONTENTS!<=-  " link contents}
@endnode 
 
