From: "rob (r.d.) hounsell" <hounsell@bnr.ca>

Folks,

  I can't seem to get this issue straight in my mind, so I'll ask here:

  What is the exact description of any scanline transparency bug in Imagine
3.0, and is it any different than what was experienced in 2.0?

  I seem to recall that any transparent object would not allow a backdrop
picture to be seen through it in 2.0. I have to admit I haven't had time to try
it in V3.

  What I'm finding now (and I don't recall if it was a problem in 2.0, or if
scanline is just not capable of this) is that objects behind a transparent
object are not visible at all in scanline mode, but are in trace. Is this a
defect, or is that the way scanline works? I'm not expecting refraction or
anything like that, but I thought that an object would at least be visible
through another totally transparent object.

  In my testing, I've placed a totally transparent plane in front of a second
object so that it coveres half the view of the second object, and then rendered
in scanline. The result is that I have half an object visible.

Thx
Rob
