There are a few other programs that stick with their interface rather 
than Amiga Standard.  ProWrite is a good example, as it's own file 
requestor has options that the asl.library doesn't offer.  It's also a 
good example on allowing the user to decide:  tool-types for opening on 
super-hi-res, workbench, and asl requestors.  This is how I'd love to see 
Imagine work ... add a couple ARexx commands and we'd be back up to 
minimal Amiga system conventions.  Actually I think someone is keeping a 
list of things they'd like done to Imagine.

Along the similar route, has anyone noticed how much slower Real3D's 
interface at eight colors is compared to Imagine?  (OK, so I really only 
had a cursory glance of Real3D, it just seemed slower)  I would hope 
that any neat 2.0 features added wouldn't impair the speed.

